===Adjective===
{{en-adj}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|physiology}} Made [[slack]] or [[feeble]]; [[weak]], [[soft]]. {{defdate|from 15th c.}}
#*'''1790''', {{w|James Boswell}}, in Danziger & Brady (eds.), ''Boswell: The Great Biographer'', Yale 1989, p. 54:
#*:It was a very wet morning. I woke '''relaxed''' and melancholy as in the country, and walked about an hour under cover, in the middle of the town {{...}}.
# Made more [[lenient]]; less [[strict]]; [[lax]]. {{defdate|from 17th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|The '''relaxed''' rules were greatly tightened after the lawsuit.}}
#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=8|passage=I corralled the judge, and we started off across the fields, in no very mild state of fear of that gentleman's wife, whose vigilance was seldom '''relaxed'''.}}
# Free from tension or anxiety; at ease; [[leisurely]]. {{defdate|from 18th c.}}
#: {{ux|en|He's a '''relaxed''' kind of guy, he never lets himself get upset.}}
#* {{quote-journal|1=en|year=2019|author=Li Huang|author2=James Lambert|title=Another Arrow for the Quiver: A New Methodology for Multilingual Researchers|journal=Journal of Multilingual and Multicultural Development|doi=10.1080/01434632.2019.1596115|page=4|text=Students and faculty members lunch at the cafeteria and naturally communicate freely with one another in a '''relaxed''' and informal setting.}}
